ONEWATER MARINE INC. (NASDAQ: ONEW)
Point of View
First half (H1) fiscal 2026, six months ended March 31, 2026
(Form 10-Q, Q2 FY26 reported April 30, 2026)
================================================================

> Top-Line Performance: Revenue declined to $822.9m in H1 FY26 from $859.3m in H1 FY25, down (4.2%) / ($36.4m) YoY, as new boat sales softened while pre-owned and service revenue held up better; the decline partly reflects exited brands and the Ocean Bio-Chem (OBCI) divestiture. FY25 full-year revenue was $1,872.3m. Management maintained FY26 guidance of $1.78-1.88bn revenue and $60-80m Adjusted EBITDA.

> Profitability: Gross margin expanded to 23.7% in H1 FY26 from 22.6% in H1 FY25, up ~110 bps, on a more focused brand portfolio and inventory optimization. Operating margin contracted to 0.3% in H1 FY26 from 1.7% in H1 FY25, with income from operations falling to $2.5m from $14.3m, driven by $14.0m of restructuring and impairment charges (including a $5.8m trade name write-down plus store-closure and headcount costs). Net loss widened to ($20.6m) in H1 FY26 from ($14.0m) in H1 FY25, as the charges and interest expense more than offset the gross margin gains. For the full year, FY25 gross margin was 22.8%, operating loss was ($85.5m) (including a $146m impairment), and net loss was ($116m).

> Cash Flows: LTM operating cash flow was ~$76.9m for the twelve months ended March 31, 2026, down from $91.8m in FY25 (year ended September 30, 2025), as the seasonal H1 FY26 cash use deepened to ($23.8m) from ($9.0m) in H1 FY25 — boat dealers consume cash in the Oct-Mar inventory-build season and generate it in the Apr-Sep selling season. The $48.7m OBCI divestiture plus operating cash funded a $56.6m Q2 debt repayment.

> Liquidity and debt position: Cash and cash equivalents were $68.4m at March 31, 2026, with total liquidity of $72.9m including revolver availability. Inventory declined to $551.4m from $602.4m a year earlier on disciplined management and the OBCI sale. Total long-term debt was $353.6m, and adjusted long-term net debt fell to 4.1x trailing-twelve-month Adjusted EBITDA from 5.1x at September 30, 2025 — a material deleveraging driven by OBCI proceeds and the $56.6m Q2 debt repayment.

> Working Capital: Inventory fell to $551.4m at March 31, 2026 from $602.4m a year earlier, reflecting disciplined inventory management and the OBCI divestiture. Floor-plan borrowings of ~$473m remain the dominant working-capital lever, though the lower inventory base eases utilization pressure.

> Operational Restructuring Plan: The OBCI divestiture ($48.7m) satisfied the "alternative cash sources by March 31, 2026" requirement flagged in the FY25 10-K. Brand exits are substantially complete and flowing through as gross margin expansion, alongside store closures and headcount reductions ($14.0m of H1 charges).

> Going Concern: The FY25 10-K's flag to source alternative cash by March 31, 2026 was effectively resolved via the OBCI sale and $56.6m debt paydown, cutting leverage to 4.1x from 5.1x. No explicit "substantial doubt" statement exists; the near-term liquidity constraint has been substantially addressed.

> Management Change: Effective August 19, 2025, the Company formalized its leadership: Austin Singleton became Executive Chairman (from CEO), Anthony Aisquith became CEO (from President and COO), and Jack Ezzell added COO to his existing CFO role, concentrating finance and operations under a single executive during the turnaround.

> Recent Issues & Restructuring-Relevant Developments: Q2 FY26 results missed consensus — revenue of $442.3m versus ~$489m expected, with operating profit down (53.1%) and a wider quarterly net loss — even as gross margin improved and leverage fell to 4.1x. FY26 guidance was maintained. No material litigation, regulatory enforcement, or labor disputes are disclosed; standard 10-K legal proceedings language only.

> Delayed SEC filing: Not flagged. The Q2 FY26 Form 10-Q was filed on schedule (results reported April 30, 2026), with no Form 12b-25 extension reported.

